I sent the updated report with file counts and collections to the CSV.

Script:

```ruby
docs = Blacklight.default_index.connection.get("select", params: {qt: "search", fl: "id, imported_location_tesim", qf: "imported_location_tes
im", "q.alt": "imported_location_tesim:(CTSN CTSNRF HSVC XC RCPXC SCACTSN SCAHSVC XCR)", defType: "edismax", rows: 10000})["response"]["docs"].map{|x| x["id"]
}.lazy.map{|x| ChangeSetPersister.default.query_service.find_by(id: x)}
fields = ImportedMetadata.fields
fields = fields.insert(2, :title, :collections, :file_count)
report = CSVReport.new(docs, fields: fields)
report.write(path: Rails.root.join("tmp", "report.csv"))

```

comments.body: The `princeton_ansible` group for staging has successfully set the Mediaflux credentials.

Connecting might be restricted due to firewall rules in place for Mediaflux:

```bash
deploy@tigerdata-staging1:/opt/tigerdata/current$ RAILS_ENV=staging bundle exec rails console
Loading staging environment (Rails 7.0.4.2)
irb(main):001:0> collection_list = Mediaflux::CollectionList.new
/opt/tigerdata/shared/bundle/ruby/3.1.0/gems/net-protocol-0.2.1/lib/net/protocol.rb:229:in `rbuf_fill': Net::ReadTimeout with #<TCPSocket:(closed)> (Net::ReadTimeout)
```

Using the Rails console, here is what I am able to diagnose:

```irb
@https = Net::HTTP.new(Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_host"], Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_port"])
request = Net::HTTP::Post.new("__mflux_svc__")
name = "system.logon"
args = { name: name }
request["Content-Type"] = "text/xml; charset=utf-8"
builder = Nokogiri::XML::Builder.new do |xml|
            xml.request do
              xml.service(**args) do
                xml.domain Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_domain"]
                # xml.domain "princeton.edu"
                xml.user Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_user"]
                xml.password Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_password"]
              end
            end
          end
request.body = builder.to_xml
doc = Nokogiri::XML.parse(response.body)
reply = doc.xpath("response/reply")
pp reply.to_xml
```

Within the reply, I find the following:

More specifically:

```xml
<message>Missing logon 'domain'</message>
```

The following *does* properly authenticate:

```ruby
@https = Net::HTTP.new(Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_host"], Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_port"])
request = Net::HTTP::Post.new("__mflux_svc__")
name = "system.logon"
args = { name: name }
request["Content-Type"] = "text/xml; charset=utf-8"
builder = Nokogiri::XML::Builder.new do |xml|
            xml.request do
              xml.service(**args) do
                xml.args do
                  xml.domain Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_domain"]
                  xml.user Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_user"]
                  xml.password Rails.configuration.mediaflux["api_password"]
                end
              end
            end
          end
request.body = builder.to_xml
response = @https.request(request)
doc = Nokogiri::XML.parse(response.body)
reply = doc.xpath("response/reply")
pp reply.to_xml
```

Attempts to request the data for all Collections seems to be timing out:

```xml
<reply type="result">
  <result>
    <session id="4458" timeout="1800" wallet="true">...</session>
    <locale>en-US</locale>
    <network-wait-timeout>30</network-wait-timeout>
    <user username="tigerdataapp">
      <name>tigerdataapp</name>
    </user>
  </result>
</reply>
```

Other API requests, such as `server.uuid` generate quick responses:

```xml
<reply type="result">
  <result>
    <uuid>1348</uuid>
  </result>
</reply>
```
This is confirmed as completed as of 03/08.
